{{Infobox song | name = Are They Going To Hang My Papa? | cover = | alt = | type = | written = 1907 | published = 1907 | writer = Owen Spendthrift | composer = | lyricist = }}
"'''Are They Going To Hang My Papa?'''" is a labor song in support of [[Bill Haywood]], [[Charles Moyer]] and [[George Pettibone]], then on trial for the murder of [[Frank Steunenberg]].<ref>{{cite journal |title=20,000 Parade for Accused Miners|journal=New York Times |year=1907 |issue=May 5 |url=https://timesmachine.nytimes.com/timesmachine/1907/05/05/104704899.pdf |accessdate=2008-10-18 | format=PDF}}</ref><ref>{{cite book |last=Adams |first=Mildretta |title=Sagebrush Post Offices |year=1986 |publisher=Idaho State University Press |location=Pocatello, Idaho |isbn=0-937834-13-0 |oclc=1766506 |pages=115|quote= |ref= }}</ref> It is written from the viewpoint of Haywood's daughter, "little Henrietta".<ref>{{cite web|title=Songs |url=http://www.idahoptv.org/productions/specials/trial/resources/songs.cfm |accessdate=2008-10-18 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20081014105012/http://idahoptv.org/productions/specials/trial/resources/songs.cfm |archivedate=14 October 2008 |deadurl=no |df= }}</ref> The miners were acquitted.
The author, "Owen Spendthrift", is usually thought to be a pseudonym, but the name is also found as the author of the words to a [[Scott Joplin]] song, "When Your Hair is Like the Snow", also written in 1907.
