'''James R. Tanner''' (April 4, 1844 – October 2, 1927) was an American soldier and civil servant. He is best known for having lost both his legs below the knee at the [[Second Battle of Bull Run]]. Serving during the rest of the war as a government [[stenographer]], he was present at the death of [[Abraham Lincoln]] and took notes that are the most comprehensive record of the events of the President's assassination. He later served as the United States Commissioner of Pensions, and helped reorganize and incorporate the [[American Red Cross]].

==Early life and military career==
Tanner was born on a farm near [[Richmondville, New York]], on April 4, 1844.{{sfn|White|White|1895|page=116}}{{sfn|Smith|1892|page=180}}<ref name="WaPoObit">{{cite news|title=Corp. Tanner, Register of Wills, Is Dead at 83|newspaper=The Washington Post|date=October 3, 1927}}</ref> He worked on the farm most of the year{{sfn|Smith|1892|page=180}} and was educated in the local public schools, graduating from high school at the age of 16.{{sfn|White|White|1895|page=116}}{{sfn|Smith|1892|page=180}} He took courses at a business school for a year,<ref name="WaPoObit" /> and then taught public school for a few months in a neighboring school district.{{sfn|White|White|1895|page=116}}{{sfn|Smith|1892|page=180}}

Tanner was just 17 years old when the American Civil War broke out in April 1861.{{sfn|Smith|1892|page=180}} He enlisted in Company C of the 87th New York Volunteer Infantry Regiment, and was quickly promoted to [[Corporal#United States Army|corporal]].{{sfn|White|White|1895|page=116}}{{sfn|Smith|1892|page=180}} (The title "Corporal" stuck with him for the rest of his life as a nickname.)<ref name="WaPoObit" /> He saw action in the [[Peninsula Campaign]] (March–July 1862), fighting at the [[Siege of Yorktown (1862)|Siege of Yorktown]] (April 5 to May 4, 1862), the [[Battle of Williamsburg]] (May 5, 1862), the [[Battle of Seven Pines]] (May 31-June 1, 1862), the [[Seven Days Battles]] (June 25 to July 1, 1862), and the [[Battle of Malvern Hill]] (July 1, 1862).{{sfn|White|White|1895|page=116}}{{sfn|Smith|1892|page=180}} He then saw action at the [[Battle of Thoroughfare Gap]] (August 28, 1862), the [[Manassas Station Operations (Stonewall Jackson)|Battle of Bristoe Station]] (August 26, 1862), and the [[Manassas Station Operations (Stonewall Jackson)|Battle of Manassas Station]] (August 27, 1862).{{sfn|White|White|1895|page=116}}{{sfn|Smith|1892|page=182}} The last time he saw action was at the [[Second Battle of Bull Run]], August 28–30, 1862. As [[Confederate States Army|Confederate]] artillery shelled his unit's position on August 30,<ref name="WaPoObit" />{{sfn|Smith|1892|page=182}} [[Fragmentation (weaponry)|shrapnel]] tore off his left foot and shattered his left leg below the knee. [[United States of America|Union]] surgeons amputated both legs about {{convert|4|in|cm}} below the knee.{{sfn|White|White|1895|page=116}}{{sfn|Smith|1892|page=183}}<ref name=nyt94>{{cite news|title=Corporal Tanner Improving; Remarkable Career of the Legless Soldier|url=https://timesmachine.nytimes.com/timesmachine/1894/02/11/106897677.pdf|newspaper=The New York Times|date=February 11, 1894|accessdate= November 8, 2008|format=PDF}}</ref>

With the Union army in retreat, Tanner was left behind to be cared for by a local farmer's family.{{sfn|Smith|1892|page=183}} He was captured by Confederate forces.{{sfn|White|White|1895|pages=116-117}} [[Parole#Prisoners of war|Paroled]] after 10 days, he spent several weeks recovering in Fairfax Seminary Hospital before being sent home to New York.{{sfn|Smith|1892|page=183}}{{sfn|White|White|1895|page=117}} He learned to walk with [[artificial limb]]s.{{sfn|White|White|1895|page=117}}{{sfn|Smith|1892|page=191}}

==Civil wartime service==
Tanner won a position as deputy doorkeeper for the [[New York State Assembly]],<ref name=nyt94/> then worked in a variety of positions of increasing responsibility for the next few months.{{sfn|Smith|1892|page=191}} During this time, he learned [[stenography]].{{sfn|White|White|1895|page=117}}

In October 1864, Tanner won an appointment as a clerk and stenographer in the [[Ordnance Corps (United States Army)|Ordnance Department]] in Washington, D.C.{{sfn|White|White|1895|page=117}}{{sfn|Smith|1892|page=191}} On April 14, 1865, he was summoned to the [[Petersen House (Washington, D.C.)|Petersen House]] where Abraham Lincoln lay dying from an assassin's bullet. During the night, Tanner took the testimony of eyewitnesses to the assassination, and he was present in the room when Lincoln died at 7:22 A.M. on April 15.<ref name="WaPoObit" />{{sfn|White|White|1895|page=117}}{{sfn|Smith|1892|page=191}}

==Post-war career==
Tanner left the Ordnance Department in December 1865{{sfn|Smith|1892|pages=191-192}} and moved back to Richmondville, New York.{{sfn|White|White|1895|page=117}}{{sfn|Smith|1892|page=192}} He took a job as a clerk of a committee in the state legislature,<ref name="WaPoObit" /> studied law with Judge [[William C. Lamont]], and was admitted to the [[New York State Bar Association|bar]] in 1869.{{sfn|White|White|1895|page=117}}{{sfn|Smith|1892|page=192}} He married Mero L. White, daughter of Alfred C. White of [[Jefferson, New York]], in 1866.{{sfn|White|White|1895|page=117}}{{sfn|Smith|1892|page=192}} The couple had two sons (James A. and Earle W.) and two daughters (Ada and Antoinette).<ref name="WaPoObit" />{{sfn|White|White|1895|page=117}}

Very active in [[Republican Party (United States)|Republican]] politics, Tanner won a [[patronage]] position as a clerk in the [[New York Custom House]] in [[New York City]] in 1869.<ref name="WaPoObit" />{{sfn|White|White|1895|page=117}}{{sfn|Smith|1892|page=192}} He was promoted to deputy customs collector and served for four years under Chester A. Arthur, the Collector of the Port.<ref name="WaPoObit" /><ref name=nyt94/>{{sfn|White|White|1895|page=117}}{{sfn|Smith|1892|page=192}}

Tanner ran for a seat in the New York State Assembly in 1871, but lost in what many considered were fraudulent elections.{{sfn|White|White|1895|page=117}}{{sfn|Smith|1892|page=192}} He ran for [[prothonotary|registrar of deeds and wills]] in [[Kings County, New York]], in 1876, but lost again.{{sfn|White|White|1895|page=117}}<ref name=nyt94/>{{sfn|Smith|1892|page=192}}

In November 1877, Tanner was appointed tax collector for the city of Brooklyn, New York.<ref name="WaPoObit" /><ref name=nyt94/>{{sfn|White|White|1895|page=120}}{{sfn|Smith|1892|page=195}}  He held the position for eight years.<ref name=nyt94/>{{sfn|Smith|1892|page=195}}  He allowed citizens to pay their taxes by mail, which was a major innovation at the time.{{sfn|Smith|1892|page=195}} Under Tanner, annual tax collections rose from $400,000 to $2 million a year.{{sfn|Smith|1892|page=195}} In 1884, he ran for [[sheriff]], but was again defeated.<ref name=nyt94/> The election of a [[Democratic Party (United States)|Democratic]] city administration in 1886 forced him from office, and he became a popular public speaker on the [[chataqua]] circuit.<ref name="WaPoObit" />{{sfn|Smith|1892|pages=197-198}}

Tanner was frequently called on to lobby Congress on behalf of veterans and made many speeches in favor of [[Benjamin Harrison]]'s [[United States presidential election, 1888|presidential candidacy]].{{sfn|Smith|1892|pages=199-200}} Tanner was appointed Commissioner of Pensions on March 23, 1889.<ref name=nyt94/>{{sfn|Smith|1892|page=200}} He supervised the operations of the [[Bureau of Pensions]] for just five months, however.{{sfn|White|White|1895|page=120}} His willingness to hire disabled veterans rather than party hacks{{sfn|Smith|1892|page=200}} and his desire to "treat the boys liberally"<ref name=nyt89>{{cite news|title=Gems from Tanner|url=https://timesmachine.nytimes.com/timesmachine/1889/04/14/106345255.pdf|work=The New York Times|date=April 14, 1889|accessdate=November 8, 2008|format=PDF}}</ref> and loosen rules so that veterans could more easily qualify for pensions{{sfn|Smith|1892|pages=203-204}} led to an investigation by [[United States Secretary of the Interior|Secretary of the Interior]] [[John W. Noble]], Tanner's superior.<ref name=nytexit>{{cite news|title=Exit Corporal Tanner: His Resignation Demanded and Given|url=https://timesmachine.nytimes.com/timesmachine/1889/09/12/102832740.pdf|work=The New York Times|date=September 12, 1889|accessdate=November 8, 2008|format=PDF}}</ref> President Harrison then requested his resignation.{{sfn|White|White|1895|page=120}} He resigned on September 12, 1889.<ref name=nytexit/>{{sfn|Smith|1892|page=209}} Leaving government service a second time, Tanner opened a legal practice dedicated to helping veterans win pension claims against the federal government.{{sfn|White|White|1895|page=120}}{{sfn|Smith|1892|page=216}}

From 1889 until 1904, Tanner was a private pension [[Lawyer|attorney]] engaged in prosecuting various claims against the government.<ref name=nyt94/> In January 1894, his legs were amputated a second time in an attempt to reduce the extreme pain from which he suffered.{{sfn|White|White|1895|page=120}}

President [[Theodore Roosevelt]] appointed Tanner to be Register of Wills for the District of Columbia in April 1904. He held the position until his death.<ref name="WaPoObit" /><ref name=nyt27/>

==Work with veterans' organizations and Red Cross==
Tanner became a member of the [[Grand Army of the Republic]] (GAR) shortly after it formed.  The organization was a fraternal association for military veterans who had served in Union armies during the Civil War.  His fame as a disabled veteran and witness to the Lincoln assassination made him popular among GAR members, and in 1876 they elected him Commander of the New York state organization.<ref name="WaPoObit" />{{sfn|Smith|1892|page=192}}{{sfn|White|White|1895|pages=117-118}}<ref name=nyt27>{{cite news|title=Corporal Tanner Dies in 83rd Year|url=https://select.nytimes.com/mem/archive/pdf?res=F10613FB3F5F17738DDDAA0894D8415B878EF1D3|work=The New York Times|date=October 3, 1927|accessdate=November 8, 2008|format=PDF}}</ref> Many attempts had been made in the previous decade to create an [[old soldiers' home]] in the state, but none of these efforts bore any fruit.{{sfn|White|White|1895|page=118}} Tanner was determined to see one built by the state.  He enlisted the help of the Reverend [[Henry Ward Beecher]], a noted [[Abolitionism in the United States|abolitionist]] and firebrand preacher, and held an organizing meeting in [[Brooklyn]] which raised $13,000 (${{formatnum:{{inflation|US|13000|1876}}}}).{{sfn|White|White|1895|page=118}}{{sfn|Smith|1892|page=193}} Tanner then criss-crossed the state numerous times, making speeches and holding rallies.  Tanner's efforts were so successful that in 1879 the [[New York State Legislature]] appropriated money for a 600-bed Soldiers' Home in [[Bath, New York]].<ref name=nyt27/>{{sfn|White|White|1895|page=118}}{{sfn|Smith|1892|page=193}} He later successfully campaigned for a home for Confederate veterans in [[Richmond, Virginia]].<ref name=nyt27/>

Tanner was elected National Commander of the GAR in 1905.<ref name="WaPoObit" /><ref name=nyt27/> In 1912, the [[United Daughters of the Confederacy]] invited him to the ceremony for the laying of the cornerstone for the [[Confederate Memorial (Arlington National Cemetery)|Confederate Memorial]] in [[Arlington National Cemetery]]. Such was his fame that he was asked on the spot to deliver short remarks to the assembled Confederate veterans (even though he was not scheduled to speak).<ref name="BeginShaft">"Begin U.C.V. Shaft." ''Washington Post.'' November 13, 1912.</ref>

Tanner was also a member of the [[Union Veteran Legion]], and was elected national commander of that association as well.<ref name="WaPoObit" />

Tanner was also active in the American Red Cross. [[Clara Barton]] founded the organization in 1881 and led it for almost a quarter century. But by the early 1900s, Barton's leadership had devolved into a [[cult of personality]] and the organization's finances were in severe straits. Barton was forced out, and new leadership established a more professional and bureaucratic organization.{{sfn|Jones|2013|page=117, 137}} Among those elected to the Red Cross' board of directors was James Tanner.  Tanner worked assiduously to win a [[Congressional charter]] for the reorganized American Red Cross, which was granted in 1904.<ref name="WaPoObit" /> Tanner later served on the organization's central committee and its executive committee.<ref name="WaPoObit" />

==Death==

[[File:James Tanner Amphitheater (28592856885).jpg|thumb|Tanner's grave in Arlington National Cemetery is near the [[Tanner Amphitheater|amphitheater]] named for him in May 2014.]]
Tanner died a few minutes after 8:00 P.M. on October 2, 1927, in Washington, D.C.<ref name="WaPoObit" /> He was buried at [[Arlington National Cemetery]] near Washington, D.C.<ref name="Ruane">{{cite news|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/local/arlington-cemetery-to-rename-old-ampitheater-for-civil-war-double-amputee-james-tanner/2014/05/16/7c85add4-dd3b-11e3-bda1-9b46b2066796_story.html|last=Ruane|first=Michael E.|title=Arlington Cemetery to Rename Old Ampitheater for Civil War Double Amputee James Tanner|newspaper=The Washington Post|date=May 16, 2014|accessdate=May 29, 2014}}</ref>

==Legacy==
In May 2014, Arlington National Cemetery officials formally redesignated the Old Amphitheater as the [[James Tanner Amphitheater]].  Tanner is buried in Section 2, Grave 877, a few yards from the amphitheater.<ref name="Ruane" />

